# IAM Access Governance — Meridian Health Partners

End-to-end Identity & Access Management governance package built for a fictional 500-bed healthcare system, covering the full identity lifecycle from onboarding through termination, periodic access certification, least-privilege role mapping, and segregation-of-duties controls.

📄 **[View the PDF (recommended — 5 pages, no Excel needed)](./Meridian_IAM_Access_Governance.pdf)**
📊 [View the Excel workbook](./Meridian_IAM_Access_Governance.xlsx) *(includes live formulas and dropdown validation)*

## What's Inside

**1. Overview** — purpose, scope, and frameworks referenced

**2. JML Lifecycle Process** — defines the full Joiner-Mover-Leaver workflow: trigger events, required actions, responsible parties, SLAs, systems involved, and audit evidence/controls for each stage (including same-day and emergency termination handling)

**3. Access Review Tracker** — a working quarterly access certification example covering 10 sample users across departments, with reviewer decisions, manager sign-off tracking, and live formula-based summary counts. Includes realistic examples of an access review catching a segregation-of-duties violation and an orphaned privileged account

**4. Least-Privilege Access Matrix** — maps job roles to minimum required system entitlements across AD, EHR, the patient portal, and Azure AD, color-coded by access level

**5. SoD Conflict Matrix** — defines access combinations that create unacceptable risk if held by a single user, with risk descriptions, mitigating controls, and severity ratings

## Frameworks Referenced

- NIST 800-53 (Access Control family)
- HIPAA Security Rule — Access Control (§164.312(a))
- ISO 27001 Annex A.9 (Access Control)

## Why I Built This

This project draws directly on hands-on SailPoint IdentityIQ experience — provisioning, de-provisioning, JML lifecycle management, and access certification support during SOX audits. I built it to formalize that real-world experience into the kind of governance documentation a GRC or IAM team relies on day to day: access review trackers, least-privilege policy logic, and audit evidence trails.

